{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496764"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:55:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:55:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1414"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1414"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.05,0.37,0.04,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54269"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1414"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39769"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"3012"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"901"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42311"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54269"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a neck of femur fracture. He undergoes a total hip replacement and is now three days post-operation. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, which is normally well-controlled. His regular medications include metformin, 4 units of short-acting insulin (Novorapid) with each meal, and 8 units of long-acting insulin (Optisulin) at night. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The nurse reports that the patient\u0027s blood glucose has reached 14 mmol/L over the past four mornings prior to breakfast, while his lunchtime and evening levels have been \u0026gt;8 mmol/L. His diet has not changed during his inpatient stay.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase the morning Novorapid dose","Add an SGLT-2 inhibitor","Commence sliding scale insulin therapy","Continue monitoring the patient","Increase the Optisulin dose"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with persistently elevated fasting blood glucose levels following surgery, despite previously well-controlled diabetes. The most appropriate management in this situation is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease the Optisulin dose\u003C/strong\u003E. The fasting blood glucose level in a patient with diabetes on regular insulin therapy is primarily a reflection of the efficacy of long-acting insulin. By increasing the dose of Optisulin (long-acting insulin), we can better control the overnight and early morning glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the morning Novorapid dose\u003C/strong\u003E (short-acting insulin) would not address the elevated fasting glucose levels, as its effects are relatively short-lived and primarily impact post-meal glucose levels. Moreover, increasing the morning dose could potentially lead to hypoglycaemia later in the day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdding an SGLT-2 inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this acute, post-operative setting. These medications require careful consideration of renal function and are generally not initiated in hospitalized patients due to the risk of euglycemic diabetic ketoacidosis, especially in the perioperative period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing a sliding scale insulin regime\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best first-line approach for managing consistently high fasting glucose levels. Sliding scale regimens are reactive rather than proactive and can lead to significant glucose fluctuations. They are generally less effective than basal-bolus insulin regimens in hospitalised patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing to monitor the patient\u003C/strong\u003E without making any changes is not appropriate given the persistent hyperglycemia over several days. Active management is required to improve glycemic control and reduce the risk of post-operative complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing diabetes in hospitalized patients, especially post-operatively, it\u0027s important to regularly assess and adjust insulin doses based on glucose patterns. The goal is to maintain blood glucose levels between 7.8-10 mmol/L for most patients. If fasting levels remain high after increasing the long-acting insulin, further adjustments or additional measures may be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The fasting blood sugar level in a patient who has diabetes (on regular insulin therapy) is a reflection of the efficacy of long-acting insulin.","Adjusting long-acting insulin is the most appropriate first step in managing persistently elevated fasting blood glucose levels in hospitalized patients with diabetes."],"references":["Sanne G. Swinnen, Joost B. Hoekstra, J. Hans DeVries. Insulin Therapy for Type 2 Diabetes. Diabetes Care Nov 2009;32 (suppl 2):S253-S259. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2811456/","Chipps D, Wong V, Ross G, Wong J. Peri-operative Diabetes Management Guidelines. In: Australian Diabetes Society [online]. 2012. Available at: https://diabetessociety.com.au/documents/PerioperativeDiabetesManagementGuidelinesFINALCleanJuly2012.pdf","Colunga-Lozano LE, Gonzalez Torres FJ, Delgado-Figueroa N, Gonzalez-Padilla DA, Hernandez AV, Roman Y, et al. Sliding scale insulin for non-critically ill hospitalised adults with diabetes mellitus. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2018 Nov 29;11(11):CD011296. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30488948/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39769"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1414"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39769"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-02T13:38:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-02T13:39:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1414"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54269"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66